reviewText: Mitchum plays a news reporter (Dick Ennis). The story goes just the way you would expect Hollywod to portray a reporter with perfect 20-20 hind sight. They bow at his feet! But, any military man would see the problem with lauding this view of the battle of Anzio. When 60,000+ troops land on the beaches, Ennis claims to have driven right into Anzio without any interference. Then goes on to claim that the American generals were too cautious and caused a lot of unnecessary death by waiting too long to march into Anzio with him. Of course, the newspaperman, lauded by Hollywood excludes examining the facts: first of all how do you move 60,000 men as fast as one man can jump into a jeep and drive down the road. Something logistics? What about supply lines. Wouldn't it have been far worse of the men march into Anzio and had no: food, ammunition, transportation, etc. Kind of a sickening sad commentary on our news media as well as Hollywood. If you are a miliary man or family, you're not going to like this movie. If you believe that the media is always right, you'll love this movie. I dislike movies that give biased opinions. In other words, why weren't the generals protrayed by powerful stars to defend themselves. Well thanks: Hollywood for ya.

reviewText: This started out as a comment to another reviewer and got to the point where I decided to just do the review thing.I don't really care about the picture on the box, but if you got the same set I did, the movie you received, "A Walk in the Sun" is a far better movie than the one you didn't get "The Battle of El Alamein".  "A Walk in the Sun" is a classic portrayal of the life of a grunt in WWII. "El Alamein" is a very forgettable movie.  In my opinion, "Walk", "Go for Broke" (the famous 442nd made up of Japanese-Americans), and the 3 Richard Arlen movies "Aerial Gunner"(Robert Mitchum billed), "Submarine Alert" and "Minesweeper" (all filmed in 1943 in the heart of the war) make this well worth the price.  Add in the other movies filmed during the war, "Gung Ho", "Corregidor", "Bombs over Burma", "The Dawn Express" and "Submarine Base" and you've got 10 movies worth watching for under $10.  George Montgomery ("The Steel Claw") might be entertaining if you like him, but Glenn Ford ("Casablanca Express"-good concept, bad movie) and Jim Brown ("Pacific Inferno") are only for the true die hard fans.  I'd also forget about the Italian movies, "Five for Hell", "Heroes in Hell", "Commandos" and "Desert Commandos".  That leaves Roger Corman's "Ski Troop Attack" (2.2 IMDB), the "Black Brigade" (which is actually tolerable - Richard Pryor, Rosy Grier) and a Yugoslavian movie "The Battle of the Eagles" (this is a decent movie loosely based upon history).Bottom line, even if you throw out half of them, 10 movies for well under $10 is a good deal even if the transfers aren't great.  I'd personally spend the money on just the first two alone "A Walk in the Sun" and "Go For Broke".  So, 4 stars because of value as much as quality.

reviewText: While many of these films aren't particularly good, a few are definitely worth the price of admission. A Walk In the Sun is an all-time classic, while Gung Ho and Go For Broke are entertaining looks at lesser known WWII stories. Films like Aerial Gunner are also interesting as pieces of propaganda that were both entertaining and educational. As with all budget titles like this, the quality ranges from fair to bad, but it's hard to argue with the price. Definitely worth picking up if you like old war movies.
summary: The good, the bad, and the ugly of WWII films

reviewText: The films, with stars for the ones I particularly liked:A Walk in the SunGung Ho**Go for BrokeCorregidorSki Troop Attack**Casablanca ExpressThe Steel ClawDesert CommandosMinesweeperBombs Over BurmaCommandosPacific InfernoThe Battle of the EaglesSubmarine AlertThe Dawn ExpressFive for Hell*Black Brigade (TV)Heroes in HellSubmarine BaseAerial GunnerSome of the films from 1943 are, while not at all good, interesting as a bit of history:  propaganda films, apparently intending to get lowlifes to enlist, as they featured lowlifes who made their lives finally meaningful by dying nobly.  The Italian films all seemed vaguely pro-Axis to me in subtle ways, but perhaps I was imagining that.Go for Broke is a decent studio B movie about the Japanese-Americans who fought in WWII, Casablanca Express is a perfectly adequate film about trying to protect Winston Churchill on his way to a crucial meeting.  The two films about black servicemen that dealt with racism they suffered might seem a bit dated, but I found them interesting.I only found two films utterly unwatchable and one, The Steel Claw, maddening.  In it, a disabled white alcoholic gets a band of guerillas to rescue a captured general on Luzon.  Though they're well-armed and experienced fighters, as the white American he automatically orders them around.  They're under fire, he yells "get down!", as if these guys wouldn't know that before the white American told them to. And his use of prostitutes is ugly and naive--the star/writer/director seems to think such women actually like their johns. It's Ugly Americanism to the nth degree.  Within twenty minutes of the film, I wanted to frag him myself, which is certainly what the guerillas would have done in real life.
summary: For the price, you can't go wrong
